A barbell partition of a graph G is a partition of V(G) into three disjoint parts {R,W_1,W_2} such that


  * R is allowed to be an empty set, but W_i≠∅ for i=1,2;

  * there are no edges between vertices in W_1 and vertices in W_2;

  * for each v∈ R, |N_G(v)∩ W_i|≠ 1 for i=1,2.

 Let G be a connected multigraph with edges labeled in [d]. A linear ordering, F_1, F_2, …, F_r, of the vertices of G is a graphical shelling if  for each i ≥ 1, the set 

    { S ⊆ [d] : every path from F_i to F_j with j<i uses some edge with color in S}

has a unique minimal element, which we will call R(F_i). Note that R(F_1) = ∅.

The cocharge of a tableau T with partition weight μ is the integer cc(T) uniquely characterized by the following properties:


* if T is a single row, then cc(T)=0;

* if S,T are jeu-de-taquin equivalent, then cc(S) = cc(T);

* if T = R ∪ S is a disjoint union of shapes with R above and left of S such that R has no entry equal to 1, then cc(T) = cc(S ∪ R) + # R, where S ∪ R has S above and left of R.

The charge of T is c(T) = n(μ)-cc(T), where n(μ)=∑_i (i-1)μ_i.

